<Author>DavidL69
<Content>Lovely Little Hotel My Wife and I booked to stay in the Le Lavoiser for our Honeymoon 2-6 Sept 2008. We arrived late nearly midnight, getting from CDG Airport is a bit of a journey. We were met by the night porter who simply gave us the key for our room and sent us to bed, which considreing how tired we were it was exactly how we wanted to be treated.The room on the 6th floor was tastfully decorated but rather small but as it a small boutique hotel i wasn't expecting a travel Inn size room.The next morning we went to breakfast and was looked after wonderfully by Nisha. Breakfast is a simple affair of Bread, pasties, yogurt, fresh squeezed organe and coffee. For and additional 4 Euro you could have eggs and bacon but the breakfast was substansial to fill us both up until well after lunch. During breakfast on the first day we mentioned to Nisha that we were on honeymoon (not with a view to get anything out of it!) We returned that evening to find a bottle of Champagne waiting for us from Nisha and the Hotel.After breakfast we approached the Receptionist to see if we could change room, as it was our honeymoon, she was more than accomodating and asked us to bring our bags to reception on our way out and she would have them transfered to the new room once it was prepared. The new room was lovely, still small but we expected this.During the rest of our stay we spoke alot to Fabienne the receptionist and found her to extremely helpful and pleasant. She recommended a lovely resturant nearby called Taste La Mode (i think) which was amazing. We had one of the best meals i have ever had!The lack of a shower curtain was entertaining but we assumed that its a Parisien thing!All in all i found the Hotel to be lovely but for us what made the stay even better was the hospitaility of the Staff. 
